[h3 id=SortGlitch 
	"Sort Glitch
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Go to any sort menu within the start menu (can be the one for items, key items, badges, tattles, the badge database, or emails) and hit A and Start simultaneously. Doing this will cause the game to think you are still in the sort menu the next time you open the menu, but the normal cursor will still be available to use (although invisible). This allows you to sort any of those categories within the start menu every time the A button is pressed.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Using an item while this glitch is active allows you to sort it to another position within the item menu during its use, causing it to remain there instead of being removed. This means that by using this glitch, you can reuse any HP or FP restoring items infinitely many times.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"https://youtu.be/Exs_MhB_D3E
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"This glitch can also crash the game if you obtain it using the sort menu for emails and then sort the emails using the first sort option while having one open to read (requires at least 2 emails to pull off).
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"https://youtu.be/SXLExTksVv8
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=SpeedGlitch 
	"Speed Glitch
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Speed Glitch refers to a sudden increase in Mario’s speed when jumping right when he returns from a battle (1 or 2 frames earlier than the double jump frame). There are four different speed values that can be produced by four different scenarios. With scenarios 1 and 2, you can also get an extra 4 units of jump height if you enter the battle with no speed along the Y-axis by jumping 2 frames after getting the initial speed glitch.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Scenario #1: Walking
	$LF
	"Mario can walk into an enemy when he is on the ground and jump first frame after leaving. In doing so, this causes Mario to reach up to 2.969 speed. If you stop walking or jump, your speed resets to normal.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Scenario #2: Backwards Walking
	$LF
	"Hitting the A button to jump with a direction at the same time as unspinning from paper mode allows Mario to walk backwards. If he walks backwards into an enemy while on the ground, the speed glitch can still be performed, but with a speed of 2.55 instead of the original 2.969 speed.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Scenario #3: Paper Mode
	$LF
	"Spin into paper mode right before entering a battle. Hold A, R, and a direction on the first or second frame after leaving a battle. Mario will have 1.19 speed as opposed to his normal 1 speed in paper mode.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"Scenario #4: Falling
	$LF
	"Depending on an enemy’s height, you can sometimes get speed glitch. After triggering a battle by jumping on an enemy, Mario slowly falls. If he is low enough to the ground, Mario can still store his Y-axis speed after the battle. Mario can be anywhere from 0 to 4 units off the ground. If he is within this range, his speed will reach 2.6775, which is the same as the speed when speed swapping. Oddly enough, Mario slows down for a bit once his invincibility frames end.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"https://youtu.be/fCmyBYsSRk4
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=SpeedSwapGlitch 
	"Speed Swap Glitch
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Moving up or down is faster than moving left or right. The game takes 2 frames to updates Mario’s, Peach’s, and Bowser’s speed normally. By moving up or down for one frame and then jumping in any direction, Mario maintains his greater speed value. Jumping first frame possible when landing from a previous jump maintains this speed value. This method requires jumping, so it is only used when playing as Mario. A variation of this is a 2 frame speed swap, wherein Mario, Peach, or Bowser can move up or down for 2 frames and then move in any direction for 14 frames without losing the greater speed value. This can be used with Peach and Bowser and occasionally used with Mario to cover more distance whenever jumping doesn’t reach a loading zone or a door completely.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"https://youtu.be/U_LBE4AA40g
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"This glitch allows you to reach the key to Grodus’ room without the use of Yoshi, meaning that if a future glitch is found that obsoletes getting Yoshi, we can still reach the end of the game.
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"https://youtu.be/VRhGzkYt6JE
	$LF
]div
[div class=p 
	"There are several ways to maintain the Z-axis speed while walking on the X-axis. This can be done because (in most cases) it takes 1 extra frame to update to the correct speed. Which method you use depends on whether or not you're capable of jumping.
	$LF
]div
[ul 
	[li 
		[b 
			"Jumping
		]b
		": Walk on the Z-axis for 1 frame, then press A (jump) and go either left or right on the next frame. This can be constantly repeated.
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				"Only possible with Mario
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
		[b 
			"Not jumping
		]b
		": Walk on the Z-axis for 2 frames. For the next 14 frames you can maintain this speed in any direction. This can also be constantly repeated.
		$LF
		[ul 
			[li 
				"Only way to do this glitch with Peach and Bowser
				$LF
			]li
			[li 
				"Mario can also do this, but it is usually slower than jumping
				$LF
			]li
		]ul
	]li
]ul
[div class=p 
	"This glitch does not work while riding Yoshi. For some reason, the game is 
	[em 
		"better
	]em
	" at updating Yoshi's speed than that of Mario, Peach, or Bowser.
	$LF
]div
[h3 id=SpeedValues 
	"Speed Values
	$LF
]h3
[div class=p 
	"Mario's speed while walking on the X-axis is 2.25 units per frame. Z-axis movement is always 1.19 times faster than X-axis speed for any given character, meaning that Mario's speed while walking on the Z-axis is 2.6775 units per frame. Peach and Bowser's X-axis speed is 2 and Z-axis speed is 2.38. Yoshi's X-axis speed is 3.375 while his Z-axis speed is 4.01625, meaning that Yoshi is 50% faster than Mario.
	$LF
]div
